Hence Mr. Mickle, notwithstanding his defence of Camoens in this respect, has thought proper in his version to smooth away its more obnoxious prominences, by omitting, in Gama’s prayer to the Supreme Being‚ his reference to St. Paul rand the Israelites‚ and by concealing the pagan term Vanus under the more general and ac- cordant appellation of CELESTJAL LovE. Yet the impropriety is not greater in thus blending the super- natural agency of the Christian religion with the my- thology of the Greeks, than in combining the former with the Gothic machinery of magic and incantation ς a practice that was common among Christian poets in every country throughout Europe, till the sublime and harmonious system first introduced by our own Milton into his immortal and unrivalled epic.
